    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "Two electrons stay farther apart than chance predicts. No force pushes them. Nothing in the Hamiltonian changes. The wavefunction does it.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Why Two Electrons Avoid Each Other With No Force",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "title"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.39,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 6,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "For two distinguishable particles, the joint probability is simply |ψ₁(x₁)|²|ψ₂(x₂)|². No preferred diagonal. No avoided region. Each particle is free to be anywhere.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.54,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 16,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Electrons are identical. If we can't say which is which, does the joint probability change? What forces the statistics?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "What forces the statistics?",
        "style": "question"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.69,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 25,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Identical fermions require an antisymmetric wavefunction: swap the two particles and the sign flips. Put them at the same x — ψ(x,x) = −ψ(x,x) — which forces ψ = 0 there.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.81,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 36,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "That zero is a node that runs along the entire diagonal x₁ = x₂ of the joint-probability surface. The two electrons cannot sit at the same point — even without any repulsive force.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.61,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 49,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4,
      "narration_text": "The mechanism: antisymmetry carves a permanent node.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Antisymmetry carves a permanent node.",
        "style": "section"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.24,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 53,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Bosons are symmetric — swap them, sign stays the same. Their diagonal becomes a ridge. Bosons bunch; fermions avoid. Opposite statistics from opposite signs.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.81,
